(49, 1, '2015-05-27 14:35:43', '2015-05-27 21:35:43', 'Given that ebikes command higher values than many regular bicycles, ebike theft continues to be a cruel menace, and this report out of Seattle offers just another example.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/peak.jpg" alt="peak" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" />\r\n\r\nAccording to <a href="https://bikeindex.org/bikes/46353" target="_blank">BikeIndex</a> and <a href="http://www.seattlebikeblog.com/bikeindex_bike/2014-izip-izip-e3-peakblack/" target="_blank">Seattle Bike Blog</a>, a 2014 IZIP E3 Peak was stolen from a condo building''s garage a few days ago, so please be on the lookout for it. It was equipped with a cable lock which was cut and left at the scene by the bike thief.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, the owner of the bike doesn''t have the bike''s serial number, and having that number can be very helpful in identifying your bike once it''s been stolen. Let this bike owner''s folly help you to err on the side of caution and register all of your bikes right now on <a href="https://bikeindex.org/" target="_blank">BikeIndex.org</a>.', 'IZIP E3 Peak Stolen In Seattle', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'izip-e3-peak-stolen-in-seattle', '', '\nhttp://www.seattlebikeblog.com/bikeindex_bike/2014-izip-izip-e3-peakblack/', '2015-05-27 14:39:56', '2015-05-27 21:39:56', '', 0, 'http://overvolted.com/?p=49', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(50, 1, '2015-05-27 14:33:44', '2015-05-27 21:33:44', '', 'peak', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'peak', '', '', '2015-05-27 14:33:44', '2015-05-27 21:33:44', '', 49, 'http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/peak.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(51, 1, '2015-05-27 14:35:43', '2015-05-27 21:35:43', 'Given that ebikes command higher values than many regular bicycles, ebike theft continues to be a cruel menace, and this report out of Seattle offers just another example.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/peak.jpg" alt="peak" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" />\r\n\r\nAccording to <a href="https://bikeindex.org/bikes/46353" target="_blank">BikeIndex</a> and <a href="http://www.seattlebikeblog.com/bikeindex_bike/2014-izip-izip-e3-peakblack/" target="_blank">Seattle Bike Blog</a>, a 2014 IZIP E3 Peak was stolen from a condo building''s garage a few days ago, so please be on the lookout for it. It was equipped with a cable lock, but there''s no word on whether said cable lock was in use to secure the bike when it was taken.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, the owner of the bike doesn''t have the bike''s serial number, and having that number can be very helpful in identifying your bike once it''s been stolen. Let this bike owner''s folly help you to err on the side of caution and register all of your bikes right now on <a href="https://bikeindex.org/" target="_blank">BikeIndex.org</a>.', 'IZIP E3 Dash Stolen In Seattle', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-27 14:35:43', '2015-05-27 21:35:43', '', 49, 'http://overvolted.com/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(52, 1, '2015-05-27 14:39:01', '2015-05-27 21:39:01', 'Given that ebikes command higher values than many regular bicycles, ebike theft continues to be a cruel menace, and this report out of Seattle offers just another example.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/peak.jpg" alt="peak" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" />\r\n\r\nAccording to <a href="https://bikeindex.org/bikes/46353" target="_blank">BikeIndex</a> and <a href="http://www.seattlebikeblog.com/bikeindex_bike/2014-izip-izip-e3-peakblack/" target="_blank">Seattle Bike Blog</a>, a 2014 IZIP E3 Peak was stolen from a condo building''s garage a few days ago, so please be on the lookout for it. It was equipped with a cable lock, but there''s no word on whether said cable lock was in use to secure the bike when it was taken.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, the owner of the bike doesn''t have the bike''s serial number, and having that number can be very helpful in identifying your bike once it''s been stolen. Let this bike owner''s folly help you to err on the side of caution and register all of your bikes right now on <a href="https://bikeindex.org/" target="_blank">BikeIndex.org</a>.', 'IZIP E3 Peak Stolen In Seattle', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-27 14:39:01', '2015-05-27 21:39:01', '', 49, 'http://overvolted.com/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(53, 1, '2015-05-27 14:39:56', '2015-05-27 21:39:56', 'Given that ebikes command higher values than many regular bicycles, ebike theft continues to be a cruel menace, and this report out of Seattle offers just another example.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/peak.jpg" alt="peak" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-50" />\r\n\r\nAccording to <a href="https://bikeindex.org/bikes/46353" target="_blank">BikeIndex</a> and <a href="http://www.seattlebikeblog.com/bikeindex_bike/2014-izip-izip-e3-peakblack/" target="_blank">Seattle Bike Blog</a>, a 2014 IZIP E3 Peak was stolen from a condo building''s garage a few days ago, so please be on the lookout for it. It was equipped with a cable lock which was cut and left at the scene by the bike thief.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, the owner of the bike doesn''t have the bike''s serial number, and having that number can be very helpful in identifying your bike once it''s been stolen. Let this bike owner''s folly help you to err on the side of caution and register all of your bikes right now on <a href="https://bikeindex.org/" target="_blank">BikeIndex.org</a>.', 'IZIP E3 Peak Stolen In Seattle', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-27 14:39:56', '2015-05-27 21:39:56', '', 49, 'http://overvolted.com/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(54, 1, '2015-05-28 08:06:18', '2015-05-28 15:06:18', '<img src="http://overvolted.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/denny-1024x644.jpg" alt="denny" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-55" />\r\n\r\nThe winner of last year''s <a href="http://oregonmanifest.com/" target="_blank">Oregon Manifest Bike Design Project</a>, <a href="http://www.dennybike.com/" target="_blank">the Denny Bike</a> from <a href="http://www.teague.com/" target="_blank">Teague</a> and <a href="http://taylorsizemore.com/" target="_blank">Sizemore Bicycle</a>, is indeed going into production this year with a run of at least 100 (and likely around 1000) examples. According to comments made in <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2upOx4Tv5Jc" target="_blank">Tested.com''s video interview with the Denny Bike''s design team</a>, we can look forward to being able to buy a Denny Ebike of our own from <a href="http://www.fujibikes.com/thebikedesignproject" target="_blank">Fuji</a> <a href="http://www.fujibikes.com/dealer" target="_blank">dealers</a> beginning in October 2015.\r\n\r\n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2upOx4Tv5Jc?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\nFuji is planning on producing two different versions of the Denny Bike, one with electric assist, and one without. This makes a lot of sense, considering that the original Denny Bike design called for some very expensive and very custom components, including a Gates Carbon Drive, a minimalist fender that uses rubber strips to rid the bicycle tire of water from the road surface by physically scraping it away from the tire surface, a custom front cargo rack, a removeable/lockable handlebar that serves double-duty as a bike lock, an <a href="http://www.arduino.cc/" target="_blank">Arduino microcontroller board</a>, an <a href="https://www-ssl.intel.com/content/www/us/en/do-it-yourself/edison.html" target="_blank">Intel Edison radio/chip</a>, an <a href="http://www.rfduino.com/" target="_blank">RFduino chip</a>, two lithium ion batteries, a custom LED lighting array, and a SRAM 2-speed automatic-shifting IGH built within a wirelessly-controlled rear hub motor. Hopefully the production version will simplify some of the electronics so that the resulting bike will be able to come in at a lower pricepoint. Pricing has not been announced, but if we had to guess, we''d peg pricing at $4,000 for the electric-assist model and $2,500 for the conventionally-propelled bicycle.', 'The Denny Bike Gets A Tentative Launch Date', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-denny-bike-gets-a-tentative-launch-date', '', '', '2015-05-27 17:30:51', '2015-05-28 00:30:51', '', 0, 'http://overvolted.com/?p=54', 0, 'post', '', 0),
